               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183906170287"></xptr>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1535" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1535" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1535" type="surname" value="RAYNE"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1535" type="given" value="EDWARD"></interp>EDWARD RAYNE</persName>
                  </hi>. I live at Merton, and am a farmer. I had thirteen trusses of hay in my barn on the 13th of May, bound, ready to go out—on the 14th, I missed two trusses—I saw them afterwards, but they were made into three bundles—I know it by the rye-straw bands, which is a very unusual thing, round the bundles, but in my barn they were in trusses—I am quite sure it is my hay.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1536" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1536" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1536" type="surname" value="HAYES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1536" type="given" value="JOSEPH"></interp>JOSEPH HAYES</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a beer-shop at Merton. I saw Remnant on the 14th of May at my skittle-ground—I saw some hay there—there were several other persons there—I did not see any thing done to the hay by any body—I said nothing to Remnant—I saw Allison, a man not in cus<lb></lb>tody—I asked him whose hay that was—he said, "It is mine"—there were three bundles—he said, "I have got it for the races"—I said, "I don't care what you have got it for, take it off my premises"—I afterwards saw Allison and Remnant with the bundles, each going in front of the house—I saw a third man, but I do not know whether it was Cook or not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1537" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1537" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1537" type="surname" value="BENTLY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1537" type="given" value="ISAAC"></interp>ISAAC BENTLY</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep a beer-shop at Merton, about twenty yards from Hayes. On the 14th of May, I saw some hay outside my premises—Allison, Cook, and Remnant took it away—I did not see it brought.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1538" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1538" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1538" type="surname" value="GROVES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1538" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM GROVES</persName>
                  </hi>. I saw the hay in the corner of my master, Mr. Hayes's field, about eleven o'clock in the day.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390617-name-1539" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1539" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1539" type="surname" value="AYTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390617-name-1539" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN AYTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a constable at Merton. I apprehended Cook on the 19th of May—on the morning of the 20th, (I did not make any promises nor ask any questions) he told me, in going from the watch-house to Wandsworth, that he, and Allison, and Remnant went to Mr. Rayne's barn and fetched two trusses of hay, and when they were going to a beer-shop, he would not take it any further, but had no more to do with it—another man took Remnant.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Cook.</hi> He asked me if I was with them, and if I would tell him the rights of it, it would be better for me—he said he had got witnesses to prove I was there—I said, "If you have, the way is to bring them for<lb></lb>ward. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I did not.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Did you never tell him you had got witnesses? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> No, I believe not—I did not tell him any such thing—I swear it—I said no<lb></lb>thing about the hay till he spoke to me—he said he brought it as far as Blind-lane, and would not take it any further—I believe I said, "Oh, did you?"—I said, "Come, Cook; it is time you had your breakfast"</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">COURT</hi>. <hi rend="italic">Q.</hi> Do you mean to swear deliberately that you put no ques<lb></lb>tion? <hi rend="italic">A.</hi> Yes—I asked him if there were not three men in the barn, and he said he believed there was one.</p>
